[[File:Tupac Amaru Shakur Center for the Arts 2016.jpg|thumb|The site where the center is located, 2016.]] '''The Tupac Amaru Shakur Center for the Arts''', based in [[Stone Mountain, Georgia]], was a performing arts center supported through the Shakur Family Foundation. The Shakur Center's mission was to provide opportunities for young people through the arts, and offers programs such as drama, dance, and creative writing classes. The organization also ran a Performing Arts Day Camp for youth ages twelve to eighteen.
The center, located off of [[Memorial Drive (Atlanta)|Memorial Drive]] was named in honor of the late American [[Hip Hop]] artist [[Tupac Amaru Shakur]], and was founded by his mother [[Afeni Shakur]].<ref name=RS_2016>Lee, Christina. [https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/what-happened-to-the-tupac-amaru-shakur-center-for-the-arts-20160706 What Happened to the Tupac Amaru Shakur Center for the Arts?]. Rolling Stone. 6 July 2016. Retrieved 22 July 2016.</ref>
==History== The center was founded in 1997 by Tupac Shakur's mother [[Afeni Shakur]] in the interest of preserving her son's legacy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tasf.org/about.asp|title=Tasf.org|publisher=Tasf.org|accessdate=14 January 2015}}</ref> It is designed to bring quality arts training to young people including some students that face many social-economic issues such as poverty.<ref name="google.com">{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LwIexeXLKecC&pg=PT152&dq=tupac+amaru+shakur+foundation&lr=&cd=11#v=onepage&q=tupac%20amaru%20shakur%20foundation&f=false|title=Tupac Remembered|publisher=Books.google.com|accessdate=14 January 2015}}</ref> Many students have enriched their artistic abilities through this center and some have even received part-time jobs.<ref name="google.com"/>
In July 1999 the foundation began its first annual summer session of PA camps with twenty campers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Bu6atp8MeBcC&pg=PA152&dq=tupac+amaru+shakur+foundation&lr=&cd=9#v=onepage&q=tupac%20amaru%20shakur%20foundation&f=false|title=How Long Will They Mourn Me?|publisher=Books.google.com|accessdate=14 January 2015}}</ref> The camp continued to grow throughout the years. On June 11, 2005 The Tupac Amaru Shakur Center for the Arts Peace Garden and visitor centre was opened.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tasf.org/news_article.asp?id=67|title=Tasf.org|publisher=Tasf.org|accessdate=14 January 2015}}</ref> The peace garden was designed as a tribute to Tupac Shakur as well as others who have died. In 2006 the music video for the single [[Pac's Life]] for the self-titled album was shot at the Tupac Amaru Shakur Center for the Arts.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iIlUNd7suew|title=2Pac - Pac's Life ft. T.I., Ashanti|work=YouTube|accessdate=14 January 2015}}</ref> Tupac's mother [[Afeni Shakur]] also went to Africa in 2006 and fostered a relationship between The Tupac Amaru Shakur Center for the Arts and The Nelson Mendela foundation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uQ0EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA66&dq=tupac+amaru+shakur+foundation&lr=&cd=20#v=onepage&q=tupac%20amaru%20shakur%20foundation&f=false|title=Billboard|publisher=Books.google.com|accessdate=14 January 2015}}</ref>
After 2006 the foundation showed signs of growth as many additional programs were created such as after school programs, dance classes and cultural exchange programs. Fees for these program resemble prices similar to those of joining a local sports league.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tasf.org/|title=Tasf.org|publisher=Tasf.org|accessdate=14 January 2015}}</ref> The foundation has also held Tupac birthday concert celebrations since 2009.{{citation needed|date=July 2016}}
==Programs== The foundation offered acting, after school and dancing classes. In addition, they offer yearly leadership and arts programs. They had also set up cross cultural exchanges with Japan and South Africa.
